title: Main Street School, December 12, 1921
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Schools. Main Street School. 6th and Main. Built 1873 and called South school; name changed to Main Street school 1889; enlarged 1900; demolished 1921. Frame. Exterior. Front view. Last day of school. Pupils being marched to new school (Bailey Gatzert) Dec. 12, 1921." Transcribed from back of photograph: “THE LAST DAY OF THE (Main Street) SOUTH SCHOOL was on Dec. 12, 1921, when the classes and their teachers were marched to the newly erected Bailey Gatzert School.  The old Main Street building was later used by the Park Department for a department stable and was finally torn down in recent years.  The foto shows the last classes that entered the building.”
intersection: 6th Ave. S. and S. Main St.

title: South School [later called Main St. School], ca. 1875
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Schools. South School (first) 6th and Main. Built 1873 and called South School; name changed to Main Street School 1889. Frame. Exterior. View from right side and back. Ca. 1875. Retouched from the original." Transcribed from back of photo: “This Rare Picture is a close-up photograph of the original South School on Main Street, which was then the stage road leading to Leschi Park (present) On Lake Washington.  Then the shoreline of the bay was less than a block away.  This picture is reproduced from a faded original, and required some retouching.”
intersection: 6th Ave. S. and S. Main St.

title: Columbia and Puget Sound Railroad Depot and Machine Shop, ca. 1880
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Railroad Stations. Columbia and Puget Sound. Railroad depot and machine shop. Built 1876?, demolished by fire June 6, 1889? Photo by Asahel Curtis." Transcribed from back of photograph: “Another picture showing the original South School (Main Street) some years after its erection in 1873.  The center building on the trestle is Seattle's first depot, on the Railroad originally constructed to bring coal from Renton and Newcastle.  This is the present site of the “Union Depot” on King street.  The lumber shed of the Retize sawmill shows to the left.  The tracks ran along what is now King street.  The Grant Street bridge later followed this route to the south.”
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. King St.
